%h2 The Bipolar Episodes

%p I view bipolar episodes as getting “stuck” in one of the phases. Overdoing the behavior of that phase, while unable to do the balancing behaviors of the other phases.

%p If a behavior is easy for you then it is possible to do it even out of phase. If a behavior is difficult for you, then it is impossible to do except <em>in</em> phase. That means easy behaviors are done too much, but difficult behaviors are done too little, leading to unhealthy imbalances.

%p Instead of just Mania or Depression, BipolarType defines four different episodes, one for each phase.

=render "cycle",
  chunks: Phase.each.collect{|p| "<b>#{p.episode}</b><br />#{p.natural_state.wrap}<p class='left'>#{p.words.ing.capitalize} is easy, but #{p.opposite.words.ing}#{%w|⇗ ⇘ ⇙ ⇖|[p.index]} is hard.</p>".html_safe}

%p How this manifests in an individual depends on your personality and which behaviors are hard for you: my mother, her father, and his mother were all bipolar, and the four of us all had different symptoms, despite most probably having the same “bipolar gene”. For example, my mother’s mania was primarily mental, and her depression physical, whereas my mania is primarily affective, and my depression mental.

%p Even the same symptoms aren’t necessarily caused by the same phase imbalance. My mother and I ostensibly had the same problem of gaining weight when depressed, but what worked for her didn’t work for me and I believe that she had #{Behavior.GPS.episode} whereas I have #{Behavior.GPE.episode}.


